    "blocks": [
      {
        "id": "title",
        "type": "markdown",
        "body": "# WA Dhufish public reconstruction \u2014 Omega stress-test report\n\nA public-evidence benchmark, not a replacement assessment."
      },
      {
        "id": "headline",
        "type": "metric-strip",
        "cardIds": [
          "card-omega",
          "card-dpird",
          "card-closest",
          "card-instability"
        ]
      },
      {
        "id": "summary",
        "type": "markdown",
        "body": "## What the public test shows\n\nOmega's working public reconstruction ended at **0.327 B/B0**, compared with DPIRD's published **0.150**. The closest tested result was **0.195** under M=0.09, but it still missed the published value and had a worse objective than the M=0.13 run. Selecting M only because it approaches 0.15 would be circular tuning, not a fix.\n\nRemoving age compositions moved terminal depletion to **0.997** and pushed parameters to bounds. This means catch and the public CPUE reconstruction do not identify depletion in Omega by themselves; the age information and its weighting are doing most of the work.\n",
        "sourceId": "omega-stress-tests"
      },
      {
        "id": "trajectory",
        "type": "chart",
        "chartId": "trajectory-comparison"
      },
      {
        "id": "findings",
        "type": "markdown",
        "body": "## Main findings\n\n1. **No single public parameter change repairs the mismatch.** The tested terminal values ranged from 0.195 to 0.997.\n2. **The current Omega fit is numerically unstable enough to require stronger multistart/profile work.** Two optimizer seeds differed by 0.060 in terminal depletion.\n3. **Age composition is the dominant signal in this public reconstruction.** Removing it changed terminal depletion by 0.671 and left the catch/CPUE-only fit on bounds.\n4. **Time-varying retention matters.** The illustrative post-2023 L50=300 mm run changed terminal depletion from 0.327 to 0.263. Omega now supports annual retention, selectivity, fishing-power and release-mortality overrides, but DPIRD's actual fitted post-2023 values are not public.\n5. **The largest scientific gap is recruitment structure.** DPIRD's current model estimates North and South recruitment deviations separately; Omega's present integrated fit does not simultaneously estimate those annual deviations.\n",
        "sourceId": "omega-stress-tests"
      },
      {
        "id": "sensitivity",
        "type": "table",
        "tableId": "sensitivity-table"
      },
      {
        "id": "quality",
        "type": "markdown",
        "body": "## Evidence quality and limitations\n\n- Exact published biology and model rules are separated from derived conversions and digitised values in `parameter_register.csv`.\n- The 2024 catch digitisation is 136.4 t versus the reported 137 t; the digitised Figure 3.21 terminal Brel is 0.149 versus the reported 0.15.\n- Catch, CPUE, age compositions and assessment trajectories digitised from figures remain approximate even when those checks agree.\n- Raw annual DPIRD input tables, the bespoke ADMB source/run files, accepted SS3 input/output files, fitted selectivity/retention parameters, exact composition weights, and failed/rejected runs were not located in the public releases.\n- This is a public-data stress test, not independent certification, an alternative accepted assessment, or evidence that the DPIRD result is wrong.\n",
        "sourceId": "public-dataset"
      },
      {
        "id": "request",
        "type": "markdown",
        "body": "## Data needed for an exact reproduction\n\nRequest these materials from DPIRD before treating an Omega comparison as definitive:\n\n1. Bespoke ADMB `.tpl`, data, parameter, report, covariance, Hessian and gradient files plus run scripts.\n2. Accepted SS3 starter, data, control and forecast files, `Report.sso`, `CompReport.sso`, version and executable hash.\n3. Annual retained catch and releases by area and sector, with reconstruction method and uncertainty.\n4. Standardised CPUE tables with standard errors, record filters, model formulae, vessel/effort effects and fishing-efficiency corrections.\n5. Raw age/length counts, sample metadata, ageing-error matrices, effective sample sizes and final weights.\n6. Fleet/area/time selectivity and retention parameters, above-legal-size discarding and depth-specific release mortality.\n7. Area-specific recruitment deviations, penalties, bias correction, bounds and stock-recruit implementation.\n8. Growth time blocks or annual k values, maturity/weight inputs and priors.\n9. Objective-function components, likelihood profiles, jitters, retrospectives, sensitivities, convergence diagnostics and rejected runs.\n10. Spatial allocation and movement data or the evidence used to assume no movement.\n"
      },
      {
        "id": "sources",
        "type": "markdown",
        "body": "## Official sources\n\n- [DPIRD 2025 West Coast Demersal Scalefish Resource assessment](https://library.dpird.wa.gov.au/fish_rar/2/)\n- [DPIRD FOP 151 external review and response](https://library.dpird.wa.gov.au/fr_fop/101/)\n- [DPIRD 2021 assessment (FRR 316)](https://library.dpird.wa.gov.au/fr_rr/133/)\n- [DPIRD 2024 resource synopsis (FRR 346)](https://library.dpird.wa.gov.au/fr_rr/264/)\n\nThe local source manifest records the exact file hashes used for this report.\n",
        "sourceId": "dpird-publications"
      }
    ]
  },
